OCI Cache with Redis

Created by Marek Kratky, last updated on May 29, 2024  3 minute read
Oracle Cloud Infrastructure (OCI) Cache with Redis is a fully managed service that provides a highly available and scalable Redis-based caching solution. Redis is an open-source, in-memory data structure store, used as a database, cache, and message broker. OCI Cache with Redis leverages the speed and efficiency of Redis while offering the benefits of OCI's infrastructure.

Key Features of OCI Cache with Redis
Fully Managed Service: OCI Cache with Redis is a managed service, which means Oracle takes care of the infrastructure, maintenance, and updates, allowing you to focus on your application development.

High Performance: Redis is known for its high performance due to its in-memory data storage, making it ideal for applications requiring fast data access and real-time processing.

Scalability: The service can scale to handle large amounts of data and high request rates, ensuring that it can meet the demands of your applications as they grow.

High Availability: OCI Cache with Redis offers built-in high availability with automatic failover, ensuring your cache remains accessible even in the event of node failures.

Competitive pricing: OCI Cache with Redis is priced based on the amount of memory you use, so you only pay for what you need.
Use Cases for OCI Cache with Redis
Session Management: Store user session data to improve the performance and responsiveness of web applications.
Caching: Cache frequently accessed data to reduce the load on databases and backend services, improving application response times.


